Net Profit (TTM/latest) (2025-09-17): 310.38M INR

Title   : Explained: Why Airfloa Rail Technology IPO listing will not double your money despite 125% GMP? 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-17T04:24:35
Fetched : 2025-09-17T05:31:30.715305
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/ipos/fpos/explained-why-airfloa-rail-technology-ipo-listing-will-not-double-your-money-despite-125-gmp/articleshow/123935130.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What is the 90% cap rule?
SME exchanges, including BSE SME and NSE Emerge, impose a regulatory cap that restricts the maximum listing-day gain to 90% above the issue price. This means even if grey market trends suggest a 125% premium, the stock cannot legally debut at more than 90% its issue price.
The rule was introduced to curb excessive speculation and volatility in SME IPOs, which often have smaller floats and lower liquidity compared to mainboard offerings.
By capping first-day jumps, the exchanges aim to ensure orderly trading and protect investors, especially retail participants, from wild swings driven by speculative trading in the unregulated grey market.
Also Read: Euro Pratik Sales IPO GMP at zero despite Ashish Kacholia Investment. Should you bid?
Why does GMP still matter?
Even though the exchange cap limits the extent of gains on day one, the strong GMP still signals overwhelming demand and investor confidence in the company. Typically, when an IPO shows such strong oversubscription -- Airfloa’s issue was bid over 300 times -- the momentum often carries into the post-listing sessions.
That means while a “double” may not be possible on debut, sustained demand could support further price appreciation in subsequent days, once trading bands gradually widen.
Why is Airfloa Rail Technology buzzing?
Founded in 1998, Airfloa Rail Technology manufactures rolling stock components and executes turnkey interior furnishing projects for Indian Railways and metro systems.
It has played a role in some of India’s marquee railway modernisation projects, including the Vande Bharat Express, Regional Rapid Transit System (RRTS) coaches, Vistadome coaches, and the Agra-Kanpur Metro.
The company’s credentials as a supplier to high-profile projects make it a critical cog in India’s fast-expanding passenger rail ecosystem. With the government pushing for indigenous manufacturing and modernisation, Airfloa stands to benefit from sustained demand in rolling stock and metro infrastructure.
Five factors underpin the hype: Participation in flagship railway projects, established track record since 1998, strong order book visibility, beneficiary of India’s infrastructure and mobility push and also the fact that very few listed players operate in railway interiors and rolling stock space.
