Title   : Jio IPO: Hidden value unlocking for Reliance or holding company discount for investors? 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-17T04:18:18
Fetched : 2025-09-17T05:44:21.102579
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/ipos/fpos/jio-ipo-hidden-value-unlocking-for-reliance-or-holding-company-discount-for-investors/articleshow/123935010.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Although listing is essentially a value unlocking exercise, the IPO route will make RIL a holding company, leading to a discount in valuations which can vary between 5-20% in this case. While global brokerage Citi said Sebi’s new listing rules have dispelled concerns around holding company discount, BNP Paribas has started factoring in a 10% holdco discount for RIL’s stake in Jio Platforms.
Under new IPO rules announced by Sebi last Friday, companies valued over Rs 5 lakh crore now need to shed only 2.5% stake, giving Ambani the optionality to bring down the mammoth IPO size to just about Rs 30,000 crore if valued at Rs 12 lakh crore.
The regulator has also relaxed rules related to minimum public shareholding norms. In case public shareholding is less than 15% as on the date of listing, minimum public shareholding (MPS) of 15% needs to be achieved within 5 years and 25% within 10 years from date of listing. The existing rule required MPS of 10% to be achieved within 2 years and 25% within 5 years from date of listing.
These two new rules, once they become applicable, will reduce the supply overhang for Jio Platforms upon listing.
Also Read | Reliance Jio IPO at $154 billion valuation? India's biggest listing and what investors need to know
Debate on Dalal Street
Citi has emerged as the most bullish voice in the debate over holding company discount. “Our view has been that hold-co. discount concerns for RIL, once Jio Platforms is listed, are unwarranted given proposed changes to listing requirements by Sebi," the global investment bank stated. "We expect the market to now align with our view as Sebi has, over the weekend, finalised these changes."
Citi values Jio Platforms at an enterprise value of approximately $135 billion and expects the planned listing in the first half of 2026 to lead to meaningful value unlocking for RIL. The bank identifies two key positives: removing a liquidity overhang of $3 billion+ share supply "which we believe the Indian market can comfortably absorb" and largely dispelling holding company discount concerns post listing given low float.
But analysts at BofA Securities have been cautious. "The key question in our view which most investors are grappling with, is what hold-co discount could be applied to Jio in RIL's sum-of-the-parts (SOTP)," the brokerage warned in a report. Currently ascribing a 5% holding company discount, BofA expects this to increase post-listing as "investors could directly invest there."
The concern is not theoretical. BofA points to approximately 30% of RIL's enterprise value coming from the Jio Platforms business, making any discount material for shareholders.
Also Read | Explained: What record-breaking Jio IPO means for 44 lakh Reliance Industries shareholders
BofA offers a sobering case study of InfoEdge, which owns stakes in Zomato and PB Fintech. The stock initially outperformed around September 2020 when both companies announced potential IPOs on the assumption that the valuation would be at high multiples in the public markets.
However, "post listing of both these stocks, we saw a correction in InfoEdge stock price on back of hold-co discount." BofA now applies a hefty 25% holding company discount in its InfoEdge sum-of-the-parts valuation.
BNP Paribas takes a middle ground but acknowledges the complexity. The French bank outlines compelling arguments on both sides: while JPL listing gives telecom-focused investors direct access reducing RIL demand, and passive holding companies in India trade at "large 30-50% discount to their underlying holdings," RIL's active management and synergies argue against steep discounts.
"We start factoring in a 10% holding company discount for RIL's stake in JPL," BNP Paribas concludes, noting that excluding this discount would increase their target price by approximately 3%, while a 20% discount would decrease it by roughly 3%.
The bank argues this discount is justified despite RIL being "an operating conglomerate" rather than passive holder, citing the precedent that "conglomerates tend to trade at a holdco discount to NAV given the associated financial, management, and operational complexities."
As 2026 approaches, the Jio IPO will be the ultimate test of whether value unlocking stories can overcome the gravitational pull of holding company discounts in Indian markets.
